# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: croatia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] The **Treaty of Berlin** (formally the **Treaty between Austria-Hungary, France, Germany, Great Britain and Ireland, Italy, Russia, and the Ottoman Empire for the Settlement of Affairs in the East**) was signed on 13 July 1878.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] In the aftermath of the Russian victory against the Ottoman Empire in the Russo-Turkish War of 1877–1878, the major powers restructured the map of the Balkan region.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] They reversed some of the extreme gains claimed by Russia in the preliminary Treaty of San Stefano, but the Ottomans lost their major holdings in Europe.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] It was one of three major peace agreements in the period after the 1815 Congress of Vienna.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] It was the final act of the Congress of Berlin (13 June – 13 July 1878) and included the United Kingdom, Austria-Hungary, France, Germany, Italy, Russia and the Ottoman Empire.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] Chancellor of Germany Otto von Bismarck was the chairman and dominant personality.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] The most important task of the Congress was to decide the fate of Bulgaria, but Bulgaria itself was excluded from participation in the talks, at Russian insistence.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] At the time, as it was not a sovereign state, Bulgaria was not a subject of international law, and the same went for the Bulgarians themselves.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] The exclusion was already an established fact in the great powers' Constantinople Conference, which had been held one year before without any Bulgarian participation.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] The most notable result of the conference was the official recognition of the newly independent states of Romania, Serbia, and Montenegro (which had de facto been acting independently for decades).
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] Furthermore, Russia regained access to the formerly demilitarised Black Sea region.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] The Paris Peace Treaty of 1856, which ended the Crimean War, had made the Black Sea a neutral territory.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] The treaty had protected the Ottoman Empire, ended the Holy Alliance (Austria, Prussia and Russia) and weakened Russia's overall position.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] In 1870, Russia invoked the doctrine of *rebus sic stantibus* and effectively terminated the treaty by breaching provisions concerning the neutrality of the Black Sea.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] The great powers became increasingly convinced that the Ottoman Empire would not be able to hold its territories in Europe.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] In 1875, the Herzegovina uprising resulted in the Great Eastern Crisis.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] As the conflict in the Balkans intensified, atrocities during the 1876 April Uprising in Bulgaria inflamed anti-Turkish sentiments in Russia and Britain, which eventually culminated in the Russo-Turkish War of 1877.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] The Treaty of San Stefano had created a Bulgarian state, which was just what Britain and Austria-Hungary feared the most.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] The Treaty of Berlin confirmed most of the Russian gains from the Ottoman Empire specified in the Treaty of San Stefano, such as Batumi and Adjara, but the valley of Alashkerd and the town of Bayazid were returned to the Ottomans.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] The regions of Ardahan and Kars were also ceded to Russia.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] The 1879 Treaty of Constantinople was a further continuation of negotiations.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] It reaffirmed the provisions of the Treaty of San Stefano which had not been modified by the Berlin Treaty and established amounts of compensation that the Ottoman Empire owed to Russia for losses to businesses and institutions during the war.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] It granted amnesty to Ottoman subjects and for release of prisoners of war.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] In addition, Article VII of the treaty provided that in the territory acquired by Russia, subjects could choose whether they wished to be Ottoman or Russian subjects for a period of six months after the agreement became effective.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] Despite the pleas of the Romanian delegates, Romania was forced to cede southern Bessarabia to the Russian Empire.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] As a compensation, Romania received Dobruja, including the Danube Delta.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] The treaty also limited the Russian occupation of Bulgaria to 9 months, which limited the time during which Russian troops and supplies could be moved through Romanian territory.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] The three newly independent states subsequently proclaimed themselves kingdoms: Romania in 1881, Serbia in 1882 and Montenegro in 1910.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] Bulgaria proclaimed full independence in 1908 after it had united with Eastern Rumelia in 1885.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] The Treaty of Berlin accorded special legal status to some religious groups and also would serve as a model for the Minority Treaties, which would be established within the framework of the League of Nations.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] It stipulated that Romania recognize non-Christians (Jews and Muslims) as full citizens.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] It also vaguely called for a border rectification between Greece and the Ottoman Empire, which occurred after protracted negotiations in 1881, with the transfer of Thessaly to Greece.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] In the "Salisbury Circular" of 1 April, the Marquess of Salisbury, appointed foreign secretary the next day, made clear his own and his government's objections to the Treaty of San Stefano and its favourable position of Russia.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] Taylor wrote, "If the congress was a defeat for Russia, it was not a complete success for Austria-Hungary or even for Great Britain...
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] The Macedonian question haunted European diplomacy for a generation and then caused the Balkan war of 1912.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] Bosnia first provoked the crisis of 1908 and then exploded the World war in 1914, a war which brought down the Habsburg monarchy.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] If the treaty of San Stefano had been maintained, both the Ottoman Empire and Austria-Hungary might have survived to the present day.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] The British, except for Beaconsfield in his wilder moments, had expected less and were, therefore, less disappointed.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] Salisbury wrote at the end of 1878: 'We shall set up a rickety sort of Turkish rule again in the south of the Balkans.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] The Kosovo Vilayet remained part of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] Austria-Hungary was allowed to station military garrisons in the Ottoman Vilayet of Bosnia and the Sanjak of Novi Pazar.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] The Vilayet of Bosnia was placed under Austro-Hungarian occupation although it formally remained part of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] Austria–Hungary annexed Bosnia in 1908, sparking the Bosnian crisis, a major European crisis that reinforced pre-World War I alliances.
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] The Austro-Hungarian garrisons in the Sanjak of Novi Pazar were withdrawn in 1908, after the annexation of the Vilayet of Bosnia, to reach a compromise with the Ottoman Empire, which was struggling with internal strife because of the Young Turk Revolution (1908).
[src:croatia/1878-treaty-of-berlin] The chaotic situation in the Ottoman Empire also allowed Bulgaria to formally declare its independence on 5 October 1908.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] The **Vidovdan Constitution** was the first constitution of the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] It was approved by the Constitutional Assembly on 28 June 1921 despite the opposition boycotting the vote.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] The Constitution is named after the feast of St.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] Vitus (*Vidovdan*), a Serbian Orthodox holiday.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] The Constitution required a simple majority to pass.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] Out of 419 representatives, 223 voted for, 35 voted against and 161 abstained.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] The Constitution was in effect until King Alexander proclaimed his 6 January Dictatorship on that date in 1929.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] The Constitutional Assembly was formed after the November 1920 Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes Constitutional Assembly election.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] The process of adopting the Vidovdan Constitution revealed major political conflicts in the new state.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] Although there were earlier plans to adopt a Constitution (see the Guidelines, the Corfu Declaration, the Geneva Declaration), the Constitution was eventually adopted by a narrow majority and overriding on a national basis.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] The SCS Kingdom is designated as a constitutional, parliamentary and hereditary monarchy, whose language is Serbo-Croatian-Slovenian.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] A unitary system was established (the theory of the tribe people).
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] The proclaimed principles of separation of powers were deformed by later provisions, but in principle parliamentarianism existed.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] Legislative power was shared by the King and the National Assembly.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] The king had a wide range of powers - legislative initiative, sanction, promulgation of laws as well as initiative and consent to change the Constitution.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] He also had the right to declare war and conclude peace.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] He also possessed extensive powers regarding the appointment of judges and the dissolution of the assembly.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] In addition, he had the classic powers of the head of state.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] The National Assembly was a unicameral representative body.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] According to the Vidovdan Constitution, citizens had political rights - voting rights, association rights, assembly and collusion.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] Voting rights were limited by the relatively high age bracket and were not enjoyed by women.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] For women, the Constitution provided for the passage of legislation that would address the issue of their suffrage, but it was not enacted throughout the life of the kingdom.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] Each member of the assembly had the right of legislative initiative, parliamentary question, interpellation.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] In the event of a change of Constitution, the Assembly dissolved and elected a new one, which had the meaning of a hidden constitutional referendum.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] The Council of Ministers was accountable to both the King and the National Assembly (Orleans parliamentarism) and the ministers did not have to be MPs.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] There was also the criminal and civil liability of the ministers, with a special State Court.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] The Council of Ministers had the right to legislate, to issue regulations for the implementation of the law and those with legal force in special cases.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] The courts were independent and organized as first instance, appellate and cassation courts (based in Zagreb).
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] Special administrative courts (State Council and Main Control) were also envisaged.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] A large number of socio-economic rights were prescribed, as well as a special Economic Council.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] The units of territorial-administrative division were districts, districts, districts and municipalities.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] The Croatian Republican Peasant Party adopted its *Constitution of the neutral peasant republic of Croatia* in Zagreb on 1 April 1921.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] On 30 June, an editorial in the People's Radical Party's journal *Samouprava* stated, "This year's Vidovdan restored an empire to us".
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] Communists, already persecuted since the December 1920 *Obznana*, responded with violence shortly thereafter.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] A member of the "Pelagićevci" faction tried to assassinate the King on 29 June.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] On 21 July, the Minister of the Interior and member of the People's Radical Party Milorad Drašković was assassinated by Alija Alijagić, member of the communist group Red Justice.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] This led to the imposition of the Law on the Protection of the State in August 1921.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] The viability of the constitution dominated the 1923 parliamentary elections.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] The Croatian Peasant Party did not accept the legitimacy of the constitution.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] After the 1925 elections, entry into the government was offered to the party by Nikola Pašić.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] The Croatian Peasant Party accepted and recognized the constitution.
[src:croatia/1921-constitution] Leader Stjepan Radić was released from prison, along with other party officials.
[src:croatia/1950s-in-croatian-television] This is a list of Croatian television related events from the 1950s.
[src:croatia/1950s-in-croatian-television] 12 May 1957 – Yugoslavia defeated Italy 6-1 in a soccer match for the 1955–1960 Central European International Cup at Stadion Maksimir, Zagreb.
[src:croatia/1950s-in-croatian-television] This match marked the first live television coverage of a sports event in Croatia, being broadcast at Maksimir Park, in Zagreb, Croatia.
[src:croatia/1970s-in-croatian-television] This is a list of Croatian television related events from the 1970s.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] The **1974 Yugoslav Constitution** was the fourth and final communist state constitution of the Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] It came into effect on 21 February 1974.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] With 406 original articles, the 1974 constitution was one of the longest constitutions in the world.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] It added elaborate language protecting the self-management system from state interference and expanding representation of republics and provinces in all electoral and policy forums.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] The Constitution called the restructured Federal Assembly the highest expression of the self-management system.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Accordingly, it prescribed a complex electoral procedure for that body, beginning with the local labor and political organizations.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Those bodies were to elect commune-level assemblies, which then would elect assemblies at province and republic level; finally, the latter groups would elect the members of the two equal components of the Federal Assembly, the Federal Chamber and the Chamber of Republics and Provinces.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] The new Constitution also reduced the Federal Presidency from twenty-three to nine members, with equal representation for each republic and province and an *ex-officio* position for the president of the League of Communists.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] The 1974 Constitution also expanded protection of individual rights and court procedures, with the all-purpose caveat that no citizen could use those freedoms to disrupt the prescribed social system.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Finally, Kosovo and Vojvodina, the two constituent provinces of Serbia, received substantially increased autonomy, including *de facto* veto power in the Serbian parliament.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] The constitution also proclaimed Josip Broz Tito president for life.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Adoption of the Constitution was preceded by significant political events that occurred several years earlier, and that marked the beginning of the federalization of the country.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] First, in the summer of 1966, Anti-federalization leader Aleksandar Ranković, one of the closest associates of Josip Broz Tito, was removed from all functions.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] The federalization ideas of Edvard Kardelj won, and thus began a gradual federalization of Yugoslavia.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] In 1968 and 1971 amendments were adopted to the Federal Constitution, through which Yugoslav Presidency as a collective leadership body was introduced (1971).
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Later that year, the republican leadership of SR Croatia was completely dismissed, which propagated their nationalistic politics.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] And in the autumn of next year (1972), a purge was carried out in the leadership of the SR Serbia.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] After all that, everything was ready for the adoption of the new Federal Constitution.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] By the words of the Constitution, all power belongs to the "working class and working people".
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] In terms of governmental structure, the provinces within Yugoslavia (SAP Vojvodina and SAP Kosovo) have received even greater rights than they had before.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Provinces had their state and party Presidencies.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Their territory could not be altered without the decision of the Provincial Assembly, provincial governments even got the right to veto decisions of the authorities in Serbia.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Josip Broz Tito, president of Yugoslavia, was named President for Life of Yugoslavia in the Constitution.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] He was also the President of the Republic and President of the Presidency of Yugoslavia.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] After his death, all his functions would be transferred to the Presidency of Yugoslavia.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] During the public discussion on the proposed changes to the Constitution, Professor of the Belgrade Law School, Mihailo Đurić was sentenced to prison after the publication of the speech in which he opposed the implementation of the planned constitutional changes.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Stressing that if something would be left from the state, it is only because in the next phase of changes we had something to bring to an end.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] *Socio-economic Planning:* The basis of socio-economic system is social ownership on the means of production, the right of a working man to self-management and enjoying the fruits of labor, solidarity and reciprocity of rights and obligations of all social actors.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Contrary to the Constitution are considered all forms of privatization of public assets, as well as "bureaucratic" or "technocratic" usurpation of resources or monopolization of decision-making.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] *Economic system:* Public property does not have a legal title holder, the holder of property rights are neither political institutions, nor economic entities, nor citizens.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Working people decide about the distribution of income, socially limited by established criteria of distribution to consumption and reproduction.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Social ownership and working people are organized in basic organizations of associated labor.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Social activities like education, science, culture and health care are organized into self-governing communities that represent the connection between the organization of associated labor and public interest.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] The work of the self-employed in private ownership and operation of farmers shall be governed by the same principles as in organizations of associated labor.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] The coordinated development of the economy through financing the development of underdeveloped republics and provinces is determined as the general interest at the level of Yugoslavia.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] *Socialist self-governing democracy:*It is defined as a specific form of the dictatorship of the proletariat which is ensured through a ban on the socio-economic and political organizations aimed at the establishment of capitalist relations.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Social self-protection is defined as the activity of all social actors to protect the self-governing constitutional order.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] The freedom of socio-political organization of working people is identified, but with the obligation to respect the framework of government socialist system dominated by the Constitution of the superior political organization.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] *Rights and freedom of men and citizens:* are limited by the interests of socialist society.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] *People's Defense* is a collateral policy of peace, opposing aggression and pressure, which is an integral part of strengthening the defense capability of the country.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] It includes the participation of all social and political institutions and autonomous organizations at all levels in defense of the independence, sovereignty, territorial integrity and self-management system.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] The unity of command of the armed forces is anticipated.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] *International relations of Yugoslavia* are based on the principles of peaceful coexistence and active cooperation of equal states and nations, adherence to the principles of the Charter of the United Nations, meeting international commitments and active participation in international organizations.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] *The role of political and trade union organizations:* the League of Communists of Yugoslavia under the Constitution has the responsibility of the political activities to protect and further develop self-governing socialist relations.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Socialist Alliance of Working People of Yugoslavia is the widest democratic front of working people and citizens and is under the leadership of the Communist Party in order to achieve political unity and action.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] In its framework it is possible to discuss social issues, launch political initiatives and harmonization of opinions to determine political attitudes.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Voluntary union organizing is integrated into the socialist self-management relations.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] The union is authorized to delegate representatives to the management and organization of joint work and to socio-political organizations, to initiate and participate directly in the self-communication and social agreements.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] *The basis of the interpretation of the Constitution and laws* of the principles of socialist self-management expressed in the introduction to the Constitution of the Yugoslav Republic.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Previous constitutions had granted the republics the constitutional right to self-determination, including a right to secede.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] In the 1974 Constitution, these rights belonged to the "nations of Yugoslavia." At the same time, the constitution included a number of provisions that could deny the right to secede.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Article 5 required the consent of all republics and provinces before the borders of Yugoslavia could be altered.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Article 283 gave the Yugoslav Assembly the power to determine alterations in the state's boundaries.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] It was not clearly defined whether unilateral secession was possible or whether this could only be done if the federal government and all of the republics and provinces agreed to it.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Out of all constituencies, the SR Serbia had the most comments on the state organization under the 1974 Constitution, which was natural given its territorial structure.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Initially, it requested the federal government to convince the province to properly interpret the Constitution, according to which Serbia was still a sovereign republic with an appropriate degree of autonomy for its provinces.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] However, after Kardelj's (1979) and Tito's death (1980) it was more and more difficult to arbitrate in disputes between the republics and provinces.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] In the mid-1980s, the Serbian leadership was requesting amendments to the Constitution, no longer only correct interpretation.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] In early 1987, thanks to the efforts of the Serbian leadership, the Presidency of Yugoslavia initiated the adoption of more than 130 amendments.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] However, some time later, there was a conflict within the Serbian leadership.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] At the eighth session of the Central Committee of the League of Communists of Serbia in September 1987, the ideas of Slobodan Milošević won, who energetically and strongly demanded the repeal of the Constitution of 1974.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] At the end of 1988 there was a shift of complete leadership in both provinces, and in the spring of 1989 amendments to the Constitution of Serbia were adopted, which significantly narrowed the powers and rights of the provinces.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] The final repeal of the constitutional provisions of 1974 in Serbia took place in September 1990, when it adopted a brand new constitution.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] In the meantime, the other Yugoslav republics had started removing the 1974 constitution.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Slovenia first removed the prefix *"socialist"* from the name of the republic in March 1990, and at the same time adopted a series of amendments that removed the socialist arrangement.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] In Croatia, after the victory of the HDZ (Franjo Tuđman), adopted amendments in 1990 which also removed the prefix *"socialist"* and changed the republic symbols as well.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] In December 1990 Croatia adopted a brand new constitution.
[src:croatia/1974-yugoslav-constitution] Bosnia and Herzegovina and Macedonia followed in the autumn of 1990, when the anti-communist forces removed the socialist system as well, and in Montenegro the removal was formally marked by the adoption of the new republic constitution in the autumn of 1992.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatian history began with the 6th century arrival of the Croats to Roman Illyria.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Settled as two duchies a century later, Croatia was granted independence in 878 under Duke Branimir and elevated into a kingdom under King Tomislav in 925.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Trpimirović dynastic succession crisis placed Croatia into a personal union with Hungary in 1102.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] In 1527, amid Ottoman conflict, Croatia aligned with the Habsburg monarchy.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] It reorganized into the State of Slovenes, Croats, and Serbs before merging into the Kingdom of Yugoslavia in 1918.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] During World War II, most of Croatia was invaded by the Axis powers who installed a puppet state known as the Independent State of Croatia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] A resistance movement restored sovereignty, emerging as the Socialist Republic of Croatia within the Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia in 1943.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatia declared independence from Yugoslavia in 1991, successfully fighting the War of Independence until 1995.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Modern Croatia is a representative democracy with a prime minister, president, and unicameral parliament.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Its constitution ensures separation of powers between the executive, legislative, and judicial branches.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatian politics reflect a multi-party system.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatia is part of many international organizations and forums including the European Union, United Nations, WTO, and NATO, among others.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] It exerts regional influence as a small power in Europe, particularly within neighboring Southeast Europe.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Since 1999, the Croatian Armed Forces have deployed internationally for a variety of peacekeeping missions and military interventions.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatia was elected to serve on the non-permanent seat of the UN Security Council from 2008 to 2009.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] A developed country, Croatia has an advanced economy considered high-income and dominated by its service, industrial, and agricultural sectors.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Its tourism sector is prominent, generating significant economic activity across the country.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatia has heavily invested in infrastructure, especially in transport routes and facilities along European corridors.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] An emerging energy power in Europe, it has strategic investments in liquefied natural gas, geothermal networks, and electric transport.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] It has extensive biodiversity, wildlife, and natural resources across its geography.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatia provides social security, universal health care, and subsidized primary and secondary education while supporting culture through media and publishing.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Alternate forms are *Khoróatos* and **Khoroúathos**).
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The origin of the ethnonym is uncertain, but most probably is from Proto-Ossetian / Alanian **xurvæt-* or **xurvāt-*, in the meaning of "one who guards" ("guardian, protector").
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The presumably oldest stone inscription with fully preserved ethnonym is the 9th-century Branimir inscription found near Benkovac, where Duke Branimir is styled *Dux Cruatorvm*, likely dated between 879 and 892, during his rule.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Latin term **Chroatorum** is attributed to a charter of Duke Trpimir I of Croatia, dated to 852 in a 1568 copy of a lost original, but it is not certain if the original was found to be older than the Branimir inscription.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The area known as modern Croatia was inhabited throughout the prehistoric period.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Neanderthal fossils dating to the middle Palaeolithic period were unearthed in northern Croatia, best presented at the Krapina site.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Remnants of Neolithic and Chalcolithic cultures were found in all regions.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The largest proportion of sites is in the valleys of northern Croatia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The most significant are Baden, Starčevo, and Vučedol cultures.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Iron Age hosted the early Illyrian Hallstatt culture and the Celtic La Tène culture.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The region of modern-day Croatia was settled by Illyrians and Liburnians, while the first Greek colonies were established on the islands of Hvar, Korčula, and Vis.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] In 9 AD, the territory of today's Croatia became part of the Roman Empire.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Emperor Diocletian was native to the region.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] He had a large palace built in Split, to which he retired after abdicating in AD 305.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] During the 5th century, the last de jure Western Roman Emperor Julius Nepos ruled a small realm from the palace after fleeing Italy in 475.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Roman period ends with Avar and Croat invasions in the late 6th and first half of the 7th century and the destruction of almost all Roman towns.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Roman survivors retreated to more favourable sites on the coast, islands, and mountains.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The city of Dubrovnik was founded by such survivors from Epidaurum.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The ethnogenesis of the Croats is a subject of scholarly discussion, reflecting the complexity of early medieval migrations and the integration of diverse populations.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The predominant scholarly consensus, based on historical chronicles, proposes that the White Croats originated as a Slavic group that migrated from White Croatia during the Migration Period.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] According to the work *De Administrando Imperio* written by 10th-century Byzantine Emperor Constantine VII, Croats settled in the Roman province of Dalmatia in the first half of the 7th century after they defeated the Avars.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Although there exist some scholarly disputes about the account's reliability and interpretation, recent archaeological data has established that the migration and settlement of the Slavs/Croats was in the late 6th and early 7th century.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Eventually, a dukedom was formed, Duchy of Croatia, ruled by Borna, as attested by chronicles of Einhard starting in 818.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The record represents the first document of Croatian realms, vassal states of Francia at the time.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Its neighbor to the North was Principality of Lower Pannonia, at the time ruled by duke Ljudevit who ruled the territories between the Drava and Sava rivers, centred from his fort at Sisak.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] This population and territory throughout history was tightly related and connected to Croats and Croatia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Christianisation of Croats began in the 7th century at the time of archon Porga of Croatia, initially probably encompassed only the elite and related people, but mostly finished by the 9th century.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Frankish overlordship ended during the reign of Mislav, or his successor Trpimir I.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The native Croatian royal dynasty was founded by duke Trpimir I in the mid 9th century, who defeated the Byzantine and Bulgarian forces.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The first native Croatian ruler recognised by the Pope was duke Branimir, who received papal recognition from Pope John VIII on 7 June 879.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Tomislav was the first king of Croatia, noted as such in a letter of Pope John X in 925.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Tomislav defeated Hungarian and Bulgarian invasions.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The medieval Croatian kingdom reached its peak in the 11th century during the reigns of Petar Krešimir IV (1058–1074) and Dmitar Zvonimir (1075–1089).
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] When Stjepan II died in 1091, ending the Trpimirović dynasty, Dmitar Zvonimir's brother-in-law Ladislaus I of Hungary claimed the Croatian crown.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] This led to a war and personal union with Hungary in 1102 under Coloman.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] For the next four centuries, the Kingdom of Croatia was ruled by the Sabor (parliament) and a Ban (viceroy) appointed by the king.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] This period saw the rise of influential nobility such as the Frankopan and Šubić families to prominence, and ultimately numerous Bans from the two families.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] An increasing threat of Ottoman conquest and a struggle against the Republic of Venice for control of coastal areas ensued.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Venetians controlled most of Dalmatia by 1428, except the city-state of Dubrovnik, which became independent.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Ottoman conquests led to the 1493 Battle of Krbava field and the 1526 Battle of Mohács, both ending in decisive Ottoman victories.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] King Louis II died at Mohács, and in 1527, the Croatian Parliament met in Cetin and chose Ferdinand I of the House of Habsburg as the new ruler of Croatia, under the condition that he protects Croatia against the Ottoman Empire while respecting its political rights.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Following the decisive Ottoman victories, Croatia was split into civilian and military territories in 1538.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The military territories became known as the Croatian Military Frontier and were under direct Habsburg control.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Ottoman advances in Croatia continued until the 1593 Battle of Sisak, the first decisive Ottoman defeat, when borders stabilised.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] During the Great Turkish War (1683–1698), Slavonia was regained, but western Bosnia, which had been part of Croatia before the Ottoman conquest, remained outside Croatian control.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The present-day border between the two countries is a remnant of this outcome.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Dalmatia, the southern part of the border, was similarly defined by the Fifth and the Seventh Ottoman–Venetian Wars.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Ottoman wars drove demographic changes.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] During the 16th century, Croats from western and northern Bosnia, Lika, Krbava, the area between the rivers Una and Kupa, and especially from western Slavonia, migrated towards Austria.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Present-day Burgenland Croats are direct descendants of these settlers.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] To replace the fleeing population, the Habsburgs encouraged Bosnians to provide military service in the Military Frontier.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Croatian Parliament supported King Charles III's Pragmatic Sanction and signed their own Pragmatic Sanction in 1712.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Subsequently, the emperor pledged to respect all privileges and political rights of the Kingdom of Croatia, and Queen Maria Theresa made significant contributions to Croatian affairs, such as introducing compulsory education.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Between 1797 and 1809, the First French Empire increasingly occupied the eastern Adriatic coastline and its hinterland, ending the Venetian and the Ragusan republics, establishing the Illyrian Provinces.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] In response, the Royal Navy blockaded the Adriatic Sea, leading to the Battle of Vis in 1811.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Illyrian provinces were captured by the Austrians in 1813 and absorbed by the Austrian Empire following the Congress of Vienna in 1815.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] This led to the formation of the Kingdom of Dalmatia and the restoration of the Croatian Littoral to the Kingdom of Croatia under one crown.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The 1830s and 1840s featured romantic nationalism that inspired the Croatian National Revival, a political and cultural campaign advocating the unity of South Slavs within the empire.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Its primary focus was establishing a standard language as a counterweight to Hungarian while promoting Croatian literature and culture.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] During the Hungarian Revolution of 1848, Croatia sided with Austria.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Ban Josip Jelačić helped defeat the Hungarians in 1849 and ushered in a Germanisation policy.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] This is around the time that Nikola Tesla was born in Smiljan.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] By the 1860s, the failure of the policy became apparent, leading to the Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The creation of a personal union between the Austrian Empire and the Kingdom of Hungary followed.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The treaty left Croatia's status to Hungary, which was resolved by the Croatian–Hungarian Settlement of 1868 when the kingdoms of Croatia and Slavonia were united.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Kingdom of Dalmatia remained under de facto Austrian control, while Rijeka retained the status of *corpus separatum* previously introduced in 1779.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] After Austria-Hungary occupied Bosnia and Herzegovina following the 1878 Treaty of Berlin, the Military Frontier was abolished.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Croatian and Slavonian sectors of the Frontier returned to Croatia in 1881, under provisions of the Croatian–Hungarian Settlement.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Renewed efforts to reform Austria-Hungary, entailing federalisation with Croatia as a federal unit, were stopped by World War I.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] On 29 October 1918, the Croatian Parliament (*Sabor*) declared independence and decided to join the newly formed State of Slovenes, Croats, and Serbs, which in turn entered into union with the Kingdom of Serbia on 4 December 1918 to form the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats, and Slovenes.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Croatian Parliament never ratified the union with Serbia and Montenegro.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The 1921 constitution defining the country as a unitary state and abolition of Croatian Parliament and historical administrative divisions effectively ended Croatian autonomy.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The new constitution was opposed by the most widely supported national political party—the Croatian Peasant Party (HSS) led by Stjepan Radić.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The political situation deteriorated further as Radić was assassinated in the National Assembly by NRS member, Serbian nationalist politician Puniša Račić in 1928, culminating in King Alexander I's establishment of the 6 January Dictatorship in 1929.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The dictatorship formally ended in 1931 when the king imposed a more unitary constitution.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The HSS, now led by Vladko Maček, continued to advocate federalisation, resulting in the Cvetković–Maček Agreement of August 1939 and the autonomous Banovina of Croatia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Yugoslav government retained control of defence, internal security, foreign affairs, trade, and transport while other matters were left to the Croatian Sabor and a crown-appointed Ban.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] In April 1941, Yugoslavia was invaded by Nazi Germany and Fascist Italy.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Following the invasion, a German-Italian installed puppet state named the Independent State of Croatia (NDH) was established.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Most of Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and the region of Syrmia were incorporated into this state.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Parts of Dalmatia were annexed by Italy, Hungary annexed the northern Croatian regions of Baranja and Međimurje.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The NDH regime was led by Ante Pavelić and the ultranationalist Ustaše, a fringe movement in pre-war Croatia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] With German and Italian military and political support, the regime introduced racial laws and launched a genocide campaign against Serbs, Jews, and Roma.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Many were imprisoned in concentration camps; the largest was the Jasenovac complex.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Anti-fascist Croats were targeted by the regime as well.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Several concentration camps (most notably the Rab, Gonars and Molat camps) were established in Italian-occupied territories, mostly for Slovenes and Croats.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] At the same time, the Yugoslav Royalist and Serbian nationalist Chetniks pursued a genocidal campaign against Croats and Muslims, aided by Italy.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Nazi German forces committed crimes and reprisals against civilians in retaliation for Partisan actions, such as in the villages of Kamešnica and Lipa in 1944.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] On 22 June 1941, the 1st Sisak Partisan Detachment was formed near Sisak, the first military unit formed by a resistance movement in occupied Europe.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] That sparked the beginning of the Yugoslav Partisan movement, a communist, multi-ethnic anti-fascist resistance group led by Josip Broz Tito.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] In ethnic terms, Croats were the second-largest contributors to the Partisan movement after Serbs.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] In per capita terms, Croats contributed proportionately to their population within Yugoslavia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] By May 1944 (according to Tito), Croats made up 30% of the Partisan's ethnic composition, despite making up 22% of the population.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The movement grew fast, and at the Tehran Conference in December 1943, the Partisans gained recognition from the Allies.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] With Allied support in logistics, equipment, training and airpower, and with the assistance of Soviet troops taking part in the 1944 Belgrade Offensive, the Partisans gained control of Yugoslavia and the border regions of Italy and Austria by May 1945.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Members of the NDH armed forces and other Axis troops, as well as civilians, were in retreat towards Austria.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Following their surrender, many were killed in the Yugoslav death march of Nazi collaborators.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] In the following years, ethnic Germans faced persecution in Yugoslavia, and many were interned.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The political aspirations of the Partisan movement were reflected in the State Anti-fascist Council for the National Liberation of Croatia, which developed in 1943 as the bearer of Croatian statehood and later transformed into the Parliament in 1945, and AVNOJ—its counterpart at the Yugoslav level.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] In addition, from areas joined to Croatia after the war, a total of 32,000 people died, among whom 16,000 were Italians and 15,000 were Croats.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Approximately 200,000 Croats from the entirety of Yugoslavia (including Croatia) and abroad were killed in total throughout the war and its immediate aftermath, approximately 5.4% of the population.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] After World War II, Croatia became a single-party socialist federal unit of the SFR Yugoslavia, ruled by the Communists, but having a degree of autonomy within the federation.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] In 1967, Croatian authors and linguists published a Declaration on the Status and Name of the Croatian Standard Language demanding equal treatment for their language.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The declaration contributed to a national movement seeking greater civil rights and redistribution of the Yugoslav economy, culminating in the Croatian Spring of 1971, which was suppressed by Yugoslav leadership.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Still, the 1974 Yugoslav Constitution gave increased autonomy to federal units, basically fulfilling a goal of the Croatian Spring and providing a legal basis for independence of the federative constituents.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] At the same time, there was a substantial Croatian diaspora during the Cold War, which included efforts aimed at forming a government in exile.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Following Tito's death in 1980, the political situation in Yugoslavia deteriorated.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] National tension was fanned by the 1986 SANU Memorandum and the 1989 coups in Vojvodina, Kosovo, and Montenegro.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] In January 1990, the Communist Party fragmented along national lines, with the Croatian faction demanding a looser federation.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] In the same year, the first multi-party elections were held in Croatia, while Franjo Tuđman's win exacerbated nationalist tensions.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Some of the Serbs in Croatia left Sabor and declared autonomy of the unrecognised Republic of Serbian Krajina, intent on achieving independence from Croatia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] As tensions rose, Croatia declared independence on 25 June 1991.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The full implementation of the declaration only came into effect after a three-month moratorium on the decision on 8 October 1991.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] In the meantime, tensions escalated into overt war when the Serbian-controlled Yugoslav People's Army (JNA) and various Serb paramilitary groups attacked Croatia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] By the end of 1991, a high-intensity conflict fought along a wide front reduced Croatia's control to about two-thirds of its territory.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Serb paramilitary groups then began a campaign of killing, terror, and expulsion of the Croats in the occupied territories, killing thousands of Croat civilians and expelling or displacing as many as 400,000–500,000 Croats and other non-Serbs from their homes.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Serbs living in Croatian towns, especially those near the front lines, were subjected to various forms of discrimination.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatian Serbs in Eastern and Western Slavonia and parts of the Krajina were forced to flee or were expelled by Croatian forces, though on a restricted scale and in lesser numbers.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Croatian Government publicly deplored these practices and sought to stop them, indicating that they were not a part of the Government's policy.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] On 15 January 1992, Croatia gained diplomatic recognition by the European Economic Community, followed by the United Nations.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The war effectively ended in August 1995 with a decisive victory by Croatia; the event is commemorated each year on 5 August as Victory and Homeland Thanksgiving Day and the Day of Croatian Defenders.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Approximately half have returned since then.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Some 19,000 Serb homes were subsequently settled by Croat refugees from Bosnia and Herzegovina.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The remaining occupied areas were restored to Croatia following the Erdut Agreement of November 1995, concluding with the UNTAES mission in January 1998.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Most sources number the war deaths at around 20,000.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] At the turn of the 21st century, Croatia experienced sustained economic growth as the nation democratized but struggled with public corruption and bouts of unemployment.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Croatian Parliament passed a set of constitutional amendments in November 2000 and March 2001 to convert from a bicameral to a unicameral body, later limiting presidential powers.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatia joined the Partnership for Peace in May 2000 and the World Trade Organization in November 2000.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] It joined the military alliance NATO in April 2009.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Adversely impacted by the 2008 financial crisis, austerity measures led to widespread anti-government protests in 2009 and 2011.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] In the latter year, parliament was dissolved in May, with Croatian president Ivo Josipović calling for new elections to quell the protests by December.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] After successfully completing negotiations from 2004 to 2013, Croatia joined the European Union (EU) as its 28th member in July 2013.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatia was affected by the 2015 European migrant crisis when Hungary's closure of borders with Serbia pushed over 700,000 refugees and migrants through Croatia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] On 19 October 2016, Andrej Plenković began serving as the current Croatian Prime Minister.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The most recent presidential elections, held on 12 January 2025, elected Zoran Milanović as president.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] In 2022, Croatia began the process to join the OECD, due to complete membership proceedings by 2026.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The nation joined the Eurozone and Schengen Area in 2023, adopting the euro as its official currency.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatia is situated in Central and Southeast Europe, on the coast of the Adriatic Sea.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Hungary is to the northeast, Serbia to the east, Bosnia and Herzegovina and Montenegro to the southeast and Slovenia to the northwest.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] It lies mostly between latitudes 42° and 47° N and longitudes 13° and 20° E.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Part of the territory in the extreme south surrounding Dubrovnik is a practical exclave connected to the rest of the mainland by territorial waters, but separated on land by a short coastline strip belonging to Bosnia and Herzegovina around Neum.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Pelješac Bridge connects the exclave with mainland Croatia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The territory covers 56,594 square kilometres (21,851 square miles), consisting of 56,414 square kilometres (21,782 square miles) of land and 128 square kilometres (49 square miles) of water.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] It is the world's 127th largest country.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Elevation ranges from the mountains of the Dinaric Alps with the highest point of the Dinara peak at 1,831 metres (6,007 feet) near the border with Bosnia and Herzegovina in the south to the shore of the Adriatic Sea which makes up its entire southwest border.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Insular Croatia consists of over a thousand islands and islets varying in size, 48 of which are permanently inhabited.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The largest islands are Cres and Krk, each of them having an area of around 405 square kilometres (156 square miles).
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] It is the largest overseas territory on the Adriatic Sea.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The hilly northern parts of Hrvatsko Zagorje and the flat plains of Slavonia in the east which is part of the Pannonian Basin are traversed by major rivers such as Danube, Drava, Kupa, and the Sava.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Danube, Europe's second longest river, runs through the city of Vukovar in the extreme east and forms part of the border with Vojvodina.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The central and southern regions near the Adriatic coastline and islands consist of low mountains and forested highlands.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Natural resources found in quantities significant enough for production include oil, coal, bauxite, low-grade iron ore, calcium, gypsum, natural asphalt, silica, mica, clays, salt, and hydropower.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Karst topography makes up about half of Croatia and is especially prominent in the Dinaric Alps.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Plitvice lakes are a system of 16 lakes with waterfalls connecting them over dolomite and limestone cascades.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The lakes are known for their distinctive colours, ranging from turquoise to mint green, grey or blue.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Most of Croatia has a moderately warm and rainy continental climate as defined by the Köppen climate classification.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Mean monthly temperature ranges between −3 °C (27 °F) in January and 18 °C (64 °F) in July.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The coldest parts of the country are Lika and Gorski Kotar featuring a snowy, forested climate at elevations above 1,200 metres (3,900 feet).
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The warmest areas are at the Adriatic coast and especially in its immediate hinterland characterised by Mediterranean climate, as the sea moderates temperature highs.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Consequently, temperature peaks are more pronounced in continental areas.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The lowest temperature of −35.5 °C (−31.9 °F) was recorded on 3 February 1919 in Čakovec, and the highest temperature of 42.8 °C (109.0 °F) was recorded on 4 August 1981 in Ploče.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Mean annual precipitation ranges between 600 millimetres (24 inches) and 3,500 millimetres (140 inches) depending on geographic region and climate type.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The least precipitation is recorded in the outer islands (Biševo, Lastovo, Svetac, Vis) and the eastern parts of Slavonia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] However, in the latter case, rain occurs mostly during the growing season.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The maximum precipitation levels are observed in the Dinaric Alps, in the Gorski Kotar peaks of Risnjak and Snježnik.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Prevailing winds in the interior are light to moderate northeast or southwest, and in the coastal area, prevailing winds are determined by local features.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Higher wind velocities are more often recorded in cooler months along the coast, generally as the cool northeasterly bura or less frequently as the warm southerly jugo.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The sunniest parts are the outer islands, Hvar and Korčula, where more than 2700 hours of sunshine are recorded per year, followed by the middle and southern Adriatic Sea area in general, and northern Adriatic coast, all with more than 2,000 hours of sunshine per year.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatia can be subdivided into ecoregions based on climate and geomorphology.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The country is one of the richest in Europe in terms of biodiversity.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatia has four types of biogeographical regions—the Mediterranean along the coast and in its immediate hinterland, Alpine in most of Lika and Gorski Kotar, Pannonian along Drava and Danube, and Continental in the remaining areas.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The most significant are karst habitats which include submerged karst, such as Zrmanja and Krka canyons and tufa barriers, as well as underground habitats.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The country contains three ecoregions: Dinaric Mountains mixed forests, Pannonian mixed forests, and Illyrian deciduous forests.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The karst geology harbours approximately 7,000 caves and pits, some of which are the habitat of the only known aquatic cave vertebrate—the olm.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Forests are abundant, covering 2,490,000 hectares (6,200,000 acres) or 44% of Croatian land area.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Other habitat types include wetlands, grasslands, bogs, fens, scrub habitats, coastal and marine habitats.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] In terms of phytogeography, Croatia is a part of the Boreal Kingdom and is a part of Illyrian and Central European provinces of the Circumboreal Region and the Adriatic province of the Mediterranean Region.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The World Wide Fund for Nature divides Croatia between three ecoregions—Pannonian mixed forests, Dinaric Mountains mixed forests and Illyrian deciduous forests.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatia hosts 37,000 known plant and animal species, but their actual number is estimated to be between 50,000 and 100,000.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] More than a thousand species are endemic, especially in Velebit and Biokovo mountains, Adriatic islands and karst rivers.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The most serious threat is habitat loss and degradation.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] A further problem is presented by invasive alien species, especially *Caulerpa taxifolia* algae.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Invasive algae are regularly monitored and removed to protect benthic habitat.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Indigenous cultivated plant strains and domesticated animal breeds are numerous.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] They include five breeds of horses, five of cattle, eight of sheep, two of pigs, and one poultry.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Indigenous breeds include nine that are endangered or critically endangered.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatia has 444 protected areas, encompassing 9% of the country.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Those include eight national parks, two strict reserves, and ten nature parks.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The oldest national park in country is Plitvice Lakes National Park, a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Velebit Nature Park is a part of the UNESCO Man and the Biosphere Programme.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The strict and special reserves, as well as the national and nature parks, are managed and protected by the central government, while other protected areas are managed by counties.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] In 2005, the National Ecological Network was set up, as the first step in the preparation of the EU accession and joining of the Natura 2000 network.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Republic of Croatia is a unitary constitutional republic using a parliamentary system.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Government powers in Croatia are legislative, executive, and judiciary powers.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The president is the head of state, directly elected to a five-year term and is limited by the constitution to two terms.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] In addition to serving as commander-in-chief of the armed forces, the president has the procedural duty of appointing the prime minister with the parliament and has some influence on foreign policy.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The government is headed by the prime minister, who is supported by deputy prime ministers and various ministers in charge of particular sectors.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] As the executive branch, it is responsible for proposing legislation and a budget, enforcing the laws, and guiding foreign and internal policies.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The government is seated at Banski dvori in Zagreb.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] A unicameral parliament – known as the **Sabor** – holds legislative power.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The number of parliament members can vary from 100 to 160.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] They are elected by popular vote to serve four-year terms.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Legislative sessions take place from 15 January to 15 July, and from 15 September to 15 December annually.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The two largest political parties in Croatia are the Croatian Democratic Union (HDZ) and the Social Democratic Party of Croatia (SDP).
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatia has a civil law legal system in which law arises primarily from written statutes, with judges serving as implementers and not creators of law.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Its development was largely influenced by German and Austrian legal systems.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatian law is divided into two principal areas—private and public law.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Before EU accession negotiations were completed, Croatian legislation had been fully harmonised with the community acquis.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The main national courts are the Constitutional Court, which oversees violations of the Constitution, and the Supreme Court, which is the highest court of appeal.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] A variety of administrative, commercial, county, misdemeanor, and municipal courts handle cases in their respective domains.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Cases falling within judicial jurisdiction are in the first instance decided by a single professional judge, while appeals are deliberated in mixed tribunals of professional judges.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Lay magistrates also participate in trials.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The State's Attorney Office is the judicial body constituted of public prosecutors empowered to instigate prosecution of perpetrators of offences.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Law enforcement agencies are organised under the authority of the Ministry of the Interior which consist primarily of the national police force.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatia's security service is the Security and Intelligence Agency (SOA).
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatia has established diplomatic relations with most world nations – 189 states in total – starting with Germany (1991) and most recently with Liberia (2024).
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] It exerts influence as a small power in this region and within European international institutions.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Since the 1990s, Croatia has had unresolved border disputes throughout Southeast Europe, namely with Serbia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Montenegro, and Slovenia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] It is a member of the United Nations (UN), the European Union, NATO, the Council of Europe, the Union for the Mediterranean, and the Schengen Area as well as the Eurozone.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Modern Croatian foreign policy objectives include enhancing relations with neighbouring countries, developing international cooperation and promotion of the Croatian economy.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] It supports 57 embassies, 30 consulates and eight permanent diplomatic missions.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The diaspora consists of communities of ethnic Croats and Croatian citizens living outside Croatia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The largest diaspora is in the United States, with a large population across neighboring Southeast Europe.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The country maintains extensive contact with Croatian communities abroad through administrative and financial support of cultural, sports activities, and economic initiatives.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatia actively maintains foreign relations to strengthen and guarantee the rights of the Croatian minority abroad.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Armed Forces of Croatia (OSRH) consists of three service branches: the Croatian Army, the Croatian Navy and the Croatian Air Force.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] They are headed by the President of Croatia as commander-in-chief while defence policy is overseen by the Government of Croatia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The military supports the foreign policy of Croatia and international security initiatives.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] It is the sole military wing of the Military Security and Intelligence Agency (VSOA).
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Armed Forces are spread across continental Croatia and capital city Zagreb, with the Navy largely based in Split.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] According to the 2025 Global Peace Index, Croatia is the 18th most peaceful country in the world.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Since the Croatian War of Independence (1991–1995), the Armed Forces have played a key role in protecting territorial integrity.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The military's first foreign deployment was in 2003 – the War in Afghanistan and Iraq War – later joining the military alliance NATO in 2009.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatia maintains a close security and foreign intelligence relationship with NATO and the United States.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The military has been deployed to various United Nations (UN), NATO and American-led missions around the world.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Since joining the European Union (EU) in 2013, it became a part of the EU defence forces.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Armed Forces have seen significant militarization and modernization since the early 2020s due to regional geopolitical risk.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Its deep integration within Europe and the U.S. has led to modern defence pacts and a robust defence industrial base.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The Croatian military is among the most technologically advanced in Southeast Europe.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatia has had military conscription since 2025, previously enacted from 1991 to 2008.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Croatia was first divided into counties in the Middle Ages.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The divisions changed over time to reflect losses of territory to Ottoman conquest and subsequent liberation of the same territory, changes of the political status of Dalmatia, Dubrovnik, and Istria.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The traditional division of the country into counties was abolished in the 1920s when the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes and the subsequent Kingdom of Yugoslavia introduced oblasts and banovinas respectively.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Communist-ruled Croatia, as a constituent part of post-World War II Yugoslavia, abolished earlier divisions and introduced municipalities, subdividing Croatia into approximately one hundred municipalities.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Counties were reintroduced in 1992 legislation, significantly altered in terms of territory relative to the pre-1920s subdivisions.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] In 1918, the Transleithanian part was divided into eight counties with their seats in Bjelovar, Gospić, Ogulin, Osijek, Požega, Varaždin, Vukovar, and Zagreb.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Since 1992, Croatia has been divided into 20 counties and the capital city of Zagreb, the latter having the dual authority and legal status of a county and a city.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] County borders changed in some instances, last revised in 2006.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The counties subdivide into 127 cities and 429 municipalities.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Nomenclature of Territorial Units for Statistics (NUTS) division is performed in several tiers.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] NUTS 1 level considers the entire country in a single unit; three NUTS 2 regions come below that.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Those are Northwest Croatia, Central and Eastern (Pannonian) Croatia, and Adriatic Croatia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The latter encompasses the counties along the Adriatic coast.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] Individual counties and the city of Zagreb also represent NUTS 3 level subdivision units in Croatia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] The NUTS local administrative unit (LAU) divisions are two-tiered.
[src:croatia/croatia-p01] LAU 1 divisions match the counties and the city of Zagreb in effect making those the same as NUTS 3 units, while LAU 2 subdivisions correspond to cities and municipalities.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia has a highly developed mixed economy.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] It is one of the largest economies in Southeast Europe by nominal gross domestic product (GDP).
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] It maintains a similarly high regional GDP-per-capita.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] It is an open economy with accommodative foreign policy, highly dependent on international trade in Europe.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Within Croatia, economic development varies among its counties, with strongest growth in Central Croatia and its financial centre, Zagreb.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] It has a very high level of human development, low levels of income inequality, and a high quality of life.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia's labor market has been perennially inefficient, with an underdeveloped investment climate and an ineffective corporate and income tax system.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia's economic history is closely linked to its historic nation-building efforts.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Its pre-industrial economy leveraged the country's geography and natural resources to guide agricultural growth.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The 1800s saw a shipbuilding boom, railroading, and widespread industrialization.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] During the 1900s, Croatia entered into a planned economy (with socialism) in 1941 and a command economy (with communism) during World War II.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] It experienced rapid urbanization in the 1950s and decentralized in 1965, diversifying its economy before the independence of Croatia in 1990.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The Croatian War of Independence (1991–95) curbed 21–25% of wartime GDP, leaving behind a developing transition economy.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The modern Croatian economy is considered high-income, dominated by its tertiary service and industry sectors which account for 70% of GDP.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia is an emerging energy power in Europe, with strategic investments in liquefied natural gas (LNG), geothermal networks, and electric transport.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] It supports regional economic activity via transportation networks along the Adriatic Sea and throughout Pan-European corridors.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia has free-trade agreements with many world nations and is a part of the World Trade Organization (2000) and the EEA (2013).
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia's largest trading partner was the rest of the European Union, led by Germany, Italy, and Slovenia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The nation has an emerging defence sector, with major manufacturers including HS Produkt and Đuro Đaković, among others.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Tourism is a major industry and economic sector.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] It has historically represented a large component the country's economic output (GDP), routinely reaching 10% to 15% of total GDP.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia is deeply integrated with the European Union (EU), contributing to overall international tourism in Southeast Europe.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Tourism is concentrated along the Adriatic coast and is strongly seasonal, peaking in July and August.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The most frequented cities are Dubrovnik, Rovinj, Zagreb, Split, Poreč, Umag, and Zadar, respectively.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The history of tourism in Croatia dates back to its time as part of Austria-Hungary when wealthy aristocrats would converge to the sea.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Tourism expanded throughout the 1960s to the 1980s before the independence of Croatia in 1990 curbed tourism until the late-1990s.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The 2000s saw a significant resurgence of Croatian tourism as it underwent nation-building with a particular emphasis on tourism revenue.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] By the late-2000s, Croatia became one of the most visited tourist destinations in the Mediterranean.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] A total of 20.2 million tourists visited Croatia in 2024.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Eight areas in the country have been designated national parks and eleven as nature parks.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] There are ten World Heritage Sites and 116 Blue Flag beaches across the country.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Factors of tourist interest are mainly culture, cuisine, history, fashion, architecture, art, religious sites and routes, nature, maritime access, and nightlife.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Tourism has been partially supported by the Croatian film and television industries due to on-location filming.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Inflation and overtourism has led to increased travel regulations and tourist costs since 2024.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Eurostat estimated that nearly 55% of EU tourist accommodation is between Croatia (117,000) and neighboring Italy (230,000).
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In 2025, Croatia was the ninth-most-visited state in the EU and third-most-visited in Southern Europe.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The motorway network was largely built in the late 1990s and the 2000s.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] As of December 2020, Croatia had completed 1,313.8 kilometres (816.4 miles) of motorways, connecting Zagreb to other regions and following various European routes and four Pan-European corridors.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The busiest motorways are the A1, connecting Zagreb to Split and the A3, passing east to west through northwest Croatia and Slavonia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] A widespread network of state roads in Croatia acts as motorway feeder roads while connecting major settlements.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The high quality and safety levels of the Croatian motorway network were tested and confirmed by EuroTAP and EuroTest programmes.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The construction of 2.4-kilometre-long Pelješac Bridge connected the two-halves of Dubrovnik-Neretva County and shortened the route to the Pelješac peninsula and the islands of Korčula and Lastovo by more than 32 km.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The construction of the bridge started in July 2018 after Croatian road operator Hrvatske ceste (HC) signed a 2.08 billion kuna deal for the works with a Chinese consortium led by China Road and Bridge Corporation (CRBC).
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The project was co-financed by the European Union with €357 million.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The construction was completed in July 2022.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia has an extensive rail network spanning 2,604 kilometres (1,618 miles), including 984 kilometres (611 miles) of electrified railways and 254 kilometres (158 miles) of double track railways.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The most significant railways in Croatia are within the Pan-European transport corridors Vb and X connecting Rijeka to Budapest and Ljubljana to Belgrade, both via Zagreb.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In 2024, the European Investment Bank committed €400 million to support the revitalization of the railway system, focusing on green and digital transformations.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In July 2024, a significant agreement was signed for the acquisition of six electro-diesel multiple units (EDMUs) to improve connectivity between Split and Zagreb.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Valued at €57.3 million and financed through an EIB loan, this project is part of the broader initiative to modernize Croatia's railway infrastructure.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Airports in Croatia are located and serves Dubrovnik, Osijek, Pula, Rijeka, Split, Zadar, and Zagreb.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The largest and busiest is Franjo Tuđman Airport in Zagreb, followed by Saint Jerome Airport in Split, Ruđer Bošković Airport in Dubrovnik and Zadar Airport in Zadar, with annual passenger numbers exceeding one million respectively.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatian airports in terms of passenger arrivals recorded more than 10 million tourists in 2018, 11 million in 2019 and 2023, 13 million in 2024.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Airports in Croatia welcomed more than 14 million passengers in 2025.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In July 2024, the airline took delivery of its first Airbus A220-300 aircraft, marking the beginning of a transition to a more modern and efficient fleet.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] This initiative includes the acquisition of 13 A220-300 and two A220-100 aircraft, aiming to enhance operational efficiency with 25% lower fuel consumption and reduced emissions.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] As of 2024, Croatia Airlines expanded its international network by introducing direct flights from Zagreb to Tirana, Berlin, and Stockholm.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Additionally, the airline launched services connecting Hamburg to Zagreb starting 1 July 2024.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The busiest cargo seaport is the Port of Rijeka.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The busiest passenger ports are Split and Zadar.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Many minor ports serve ferries connecting numerous islands and coastal cities with ferry lines to several cities in Italy.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The largest river port is port of Vukovar, located on the Danube in Vukovar, representing the nation's outlet to the Pan-European transport corridor VII.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] 610 kilometres (380 miles) of crude oil pipelines serve Croatia, connecting the Rijeka oil terminal with refineries in Rijeka and Sisak, and several transhipment terminals.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The system has a capacity of 20 million tonnes per year.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The natural gas transportation system comprises 2,113 kilometres (1,313 miles) of trunk and regional pipelines, and more than 300 associated structures, connecting production rigs, the Okoli natural gas storage facility, 27 end-users and 37 distribution systems.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia also plays an important role in regional energy security.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The floating liquefied natural gas import terminal off Krk island LNG Hrvatska commenced operations on 1 January 2021, positioning Croatia as a regional energy leader and contributing to diversification of Europe's energy supply.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In 2010, Croatian energy production covered 85% of nationwide natural gas and 19% of oil demand.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In 2016, Croatia's primary energy production involved natural gas (24.8%), hydropower (28.3%), crude oil (13.6%), fuelwood (27.6%), and heat pumps and other renewable energy sources (5.7%).
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In 2017, net total electrical power production reached 11,543 GWh, while it imported 12,157 GWh or about 40% of its electric power energy needs.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia co-owns 50% of the Krško Nuclear Power Plant with neighboring Slovenia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] This power plant supplies a large part of Croatian imports and provides 15% of the nation's electricity.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] According to Eurostat in 2026, Croatia has the highest quantity of water resources per capita in the EU (30,000 m3).
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] With an estimated population of 3.87 million in 2024, Croatia ranks 128th by population in the world.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Its 2018 population density was 72.9 inhabitants per square kilometre, making Croatia one of the more sparsely populated European countries.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The overall life expectancy in Croatia at birth was 77.7 years in 2024.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The total fertility rate of 1.46 children per mother, is one of the lowest in the world, far below the replacement rate of 2.1; it remains considerably below the high of 6.18 children rate in 1885.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia's death rate has continuously exceeded its birth rate since 1998.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia subsequently has one of the world's oldest populations, with an average age of 45.1 years.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The population rose steadily from 2.1 million in 1857 until 1991, when it peaked at 4.7 million, with the exceptions of censuses taken in 1921 and 1948, i.e., following the world wars.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The natural growth rate is negative with the demographic transition completed in the 1970s.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In recent years, the Croatian government has been pressured to increase permit quotas for foreign workers, reaching an all-time high of 68.100 in 2019.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In accordance with its immigration policy, Croatia is trying to entice emigrants to return.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] From 2008 to 2018, Croatia's population dropped by 10%.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Historic demographic shifts are closely tied to Croatia's nation-building efforts and the related 1990s War of Independence.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The war displaced large numbers of the population and emigration increased.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In 1991, in predominantly occupied areas, more than 400,000 Croats were either removed from their homes by Serb forces or fled the violence.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] During the war's final days, about 150,000–200,000 Serbs fled before the arrival of Croatian forces during Operation Storm.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] After the war, the number of displaced persons fell to about 250,000.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The Croatian government cared for displaced persons via the social security system and the Office of Displaced Persons and Refugees.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Most of the territories abandoned during the war were settled by Croat refugees from Bosnia and Herzegovina, mostly from north-western Bosnia, while some displaced people returned to their homes.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] According to the 2024 Croatian Bureau of Statistics report, 12.5% to 14.6% of Croatia's population were immigrants.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Approximately 4 million Croats live abroad.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Freedom of religion is a constitutional right that protects all religious communities as equal before the law and considers them separate from the state.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] According to the 2021 census, 87.39% of Croatians identify as Christian; of these, Catholics make up the largest group, accounting for 78.97% of the population, after which follows Eastern Orthodoxy (3.32%), Protestantism (0.26%), and other Christians (4.83%).
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The largest religion after Christianity is Islam (1.32%).
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] 4.71% of the population describe itself as non-religious.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In the Eurostat Eurobarometer Poll of 2010, 69% of the population responded that "they believe there is a God".
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In a 2009 Gallup poll, 70% answered yes to the question "Is religion an important part of your daily life?" Approximately 24% of the population attend religious services regularly.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatian is the official language of the Republic of Croatia and has been an official language of the European Union since Croatia's accession in 2013.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatian replaced Latin as the official language of the Croatian government in the 19th century.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Following the Vienna Literary Agreement in 1850, the language and its Latin alphabet underwent reforms to create an unified "Croatian or Serbian" or "Serbo-Croatian" standard, which under various names became the official language of Yugoslavia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In SFR Yugoslavia, from 1972 to 1989, the language was constitutionally designated as the "Croatian literary language" and the "Croatian or Serbian language".
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] It was the result of a resistance to and secession from "Serbo-Croatian" in the form of the Declaration on the Status and Name of the Croatian Literary Language as part of the Croatian Spring.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Since gaining independence in the early 1990s, the Republic of Croatia constitutionally designates the language as "Croatian language" and regulates it through linguistic prescription.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The long-standing aspiration for development of its own expressions and thus enrichment of the language, as opposed to the adoption of foreign solutions in the form of loanwords, has been described by linguists as Croatian linguistic purism.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Minority languages are in official use in local government units where more than a third of the population consists of national minorities or where local enabling legislation applies.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Those languages are Czech, Hungarian, Italian, Serbian, and Slovak.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The following minority languages are also recognised: Albanian, Bosnian, Bulgarian, German, Hebrew, Macedonian, Montenegrin, Polish, Romanian, Istro-Romanian, Romani, Russian, Rusyn, Slovene, Turkish, and Ukrainian.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] According to the 2021 Census, 95.25% of citizens declared Croatian as their native language, 1.16% declared Serbian as their native language, while no other language reaches 0.26%.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatian is a member of the South Slavic languages and is written using the Latin alphabet.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] There are three major dialects spoken on the territory of Croatia, with standard Croatian based on the Shtokavian dialect.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The Chakavian and Kajkavian dialects are distinguished from Shtokavian by their lexicon, phonology and syntax.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] A 2011 survey revealed that 78% of Croats claim knowledge of at least one foreign language.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] According to a 2005 EC survey, 49% of Croats speak English as the second language, 34% speak German, 14% speak Italian, 10% speak French, 4% speak Russian and 2% speak Spanish.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] However several large municipalities support minority languages.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] A majority of Slovenes (59%) have some knowledge of Croatian.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The country is a part of various language-based international associations, most notably the European Union Language Association.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] is the largest Croatian university and the oldest university in Southeastern Europe.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] As of 2024, the literacy rate in Croatia was 99.45%.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Primary education in Croatia starts at the age of six or seven and consists of eight grades.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In 2007 a law was passed to increase free, noncompulsory education until 18 years of age.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Compulsory education consists of eight grades of elementary school.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Secondary education is provided by gymnasiums and vocational schools.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] As of the 2022–23 school year, there were 2,073 elementary schools and 738 upper secondary schools in Croatia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Primary and secondary education are also available in languages of recognised minorities in Croatia, where classes are held in Czech, Hungarian, Italian, Serbian, German and Slovak languages.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] There are 133 elementary and secondary level music and art schools, as well as 83 elementary and 44 secondary schools for disabled children and youth and 11 elementary and 52 secondary schools for adults.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Nationwide leaving exams (Croatian: *državna matura*) were introduced for secondary education students in the school year 2009–2010.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] It comprises three compulsory subjects (Croatian language, mathematics, and a foreign language) and optional subjects and is a prerequisite for university education.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia has eight public universities and two private universities.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The University of Zadar, the first university in Croatia, was founded in 1396 and remained active until 1807, when other institutions of higher education took over until the foundation of the renewed University of Zadar in 2002.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The University of Zagreb, founded in 1669, is the oldest continuously operating university in Southeast Europe.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] There are also 15 polytechnics, of which two are private, and 30 higher education institutions, of which 27 are private.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In total, there are 131 institutions of higher education in Croatia, attended by more than 160 thousand students.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In 2022, Croatia's research and development (R&D) expenditure was approximately 1.43% of GDP.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Among the scientific institutes operating in Croatia, the largest is the Ruđer Bošković Institute in Zagreb.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The Croatian Academy of Sciences and Arts in Zagreb is a learned society promoting language, culture, arts and science from its inception in 1866.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia was ranked 40th in the Global Innovation Index in 2025.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The European Investment Bank provided digital infrastructure and equipment to around 150 primary and secondary schools in Croatia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Twenty of these schools got specialised assistance in the form of gear, software, and services to help them integrate the teaching and administrative operations.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In 2024, the EIB extended a €207 million loan to the City of Zagreb for infrastructure upgrades, including investments in renewable energy, energy efficiency projects, social and affordable housing, schools, and kindergartens.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Additionally, the EIB signed a €49 million loan with the City of Split to co-finance its 2023–2027 multi-sector investment programme, which includes refurbishing public buildings, increasing energy efficiency, and improving technical equipment for public information and communication.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia has a universal health care system, whose roots can be traced back to the Hungarian-Croatian Parliament Act of 1891, providing a form of mandatory insurance of all factory workers and craftsmen.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The population is covered by a basic health insurance plan provided by statute and optional insurance.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In 2017, annual healthcare related expenditures reached 22.2 billion kuna (around €3.0 billion).
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Healthcare expenditures make up only 0.6% of private health insurance and public spending.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In 2022, Croatia spent around 7.2% of its GDP on healthcare.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In 2025, Croatia ranked 53rd in the world in life expectancy with 75.8 years for men and 81.9 years for women, and it had a low infant mortality rate of 3.3 per 1,000 live births.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] There are hundreds of healthcare institutions in Croatia, including 75 hospitals, and 13 clinics with 23,049 beds.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The hospitals and clinics care for more than 700 thousand patients per year and employ 6,642 medical doctors, including 4,773 specialists.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] There is a total of 69,841 health workers.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] There are 119 emergency units in health centres, responding to more than a million calls.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The principal cause of death in 2022 was cardiovascular disease at 34.3% for men and 43.8% for women, followed by hypertensive disease.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In 2022 it was estimated that 37% of Croatians are smokers.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] According to 2022 data, 35.65% of the Croatian adult population is obese.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Because of its geographical position, Croatia represents a blend of four different cultural spheres.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] It has been a crossroads of influences from western culture and the east since the schism between the Western Roman Empire and the Byzantine Empire, and also from Central Europe and Mediterranean culture.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The Illyrian movement was the most significant period of national cultural history, as the 19th century proved crucial to the emancipation of Croatians and saw unprecedented developments in all fields of art and culture, giving rise to many historical figures.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The Ministry of Culture is tasked with preserving the nation's cultural and natural heritage and overseeing its development.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Further activities supporting the development of culture are undertaken at the local government level.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The UNESCO's World Heritage List includes ten sites in Croatia and a list of Intangible Cultural Heritage of Croatia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The country is rich with intangible culture and holds 15 of UNESCO's World's intangible culture masterpieces, ranking fourth in the world.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] A global cultural contribution from Croatia is the necktie, derived from the cravat originally worn by the 17th-century Croatian mercenaries in France.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In 2019, Croatia had 95 professional theatres, 30 professional children's theatres, and 51 amateur theatres visited by more than 2.27 million viewers per year.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Professional theatres employ 1,195 artists.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] There are 42 professional orchestras, ensembles, and choirs, attracting an annual attendance of 297 thousand.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] There are 75 cinemas with 166 screens and attendance of 5.026 million.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia has 222 museums, visited by more than 2.71 million people in 2023.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Furthermore, there are 1,768 libraries, containing 26.8 million volumes, and 19 state archives.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The book publishing market is dominated by several major publishers and the industry's centrepiece event—Interliber exhibition held annually at Zagreb Fair.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Architecture in Croatia reflects influences of bordering nations.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Austrian and Hungarian influence is visible in public spaces and buildings in the north and the central regions, architecture found along coasts of Dalmatia and Istria exhibits Venetian influence.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Squares named after culture heroes, parks, and pedestrian-only zones, are features of Croatian towns and cities, especially where large scale Baroque urban planning took place, for instance in Osijek (Tvrđa), Varaždin, and Karlovac.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The subsequent influence of the Art Nouveau was reflected in contemporary architecture.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The architecture is the Mediterranean with a Venetian and Renaissance influence in major coastal urban areas exemplified in works of Giorgio da Sebenico and Nicolas of Florence such as the Cathedral of St.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The oldest preserved examples of Croatian architecture are the 9th-century churches, with the largest and the most representative among them being Church of St.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Besides the architecture encompassing the oldest artworks, there is a history of artists in Croatia reaching the Middle Ages.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In that period the stone portal of the Trogir Cathedral was made by Radovan, representing the most important monument of Romanesque sculpture from Medieval Croatia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The Renaissance had the greatest impact on the Adriatic Sea coast since the remainder was embroiled in the Hundred Years' Croatian–Ottoman War.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] With the waning of the Ottoman Empire, art flourished during the Baroque and Rococo.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The 19th and 20th centuries brought affirmation of numerous Croatian artisans, helped by several patrons of the arts such as bishop Josip Juraj Strossmayer.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatian artists of the period achieving renown were Vlaho Bukovac, Ivan Meštrović, and Ivan Generalić.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The Baška tablet, a stone inscribed with the glagolitic alphabet found on the Krk island and dated to c.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] 1100, is considered to be the oldest surviving prose in Croatian.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The beginning of more vigorous development of Croatian literature is marked by the Renaissance and Marko Marulić.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatian music varies from classical operas to modern-day rock.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Vatroslav Lisinski created the country's first opera, *Love and Malice*, in 1846.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Ivan Zajc composed more than a thousand pieces of music, including masses and oratorios.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Pianist Ivo Pogorelić has performed across the world.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In Croatia, the Constitution guarantees the freedom of the press and the freedom of speech.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia ranked 64th in the 2019 Press Freedom Index report compiled by Reporters Without Borders which noted that journalists who investigate corruption, organised crime or war crimes face challenges and that the Government was trying to influence the public broadcaster HRT's editorial policies.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In its 2019 Freedom in the World report, the Freedom House classified freedoms of press and speech in Croatia as generally free from political interference and manipulation, noting that journalists still face threats and occasional attacks.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The state-owned news agency HINA runs a wire service in Croatian and English on politics, economics, society, and culture.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Also, there are 21 regional or local DVB-T television channels.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The HRT is also broadcasting a satellite TV channel.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In 2020, there were 147 radio stations and 27 TV stations in Croatia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Cable television and IPTV networks are gaining ground.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Cable television already serves 450 thousand people, around 10% of the total population of the country.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In 2010, 267 newspapers and 2,676 magazines were published in Croatia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The print media market is dominated by the Croatian-owned Hanza Media and Austrian-owned Styria Media Group who publish their flagship dailies *Jutarnji list*, *Večernji list* and *24sata*.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Other influential newspapers are *Novi list* and *Slobodna Dalmacija*.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In 2020, *24sata* was the most widely circulated daily newspaper, followed by *Večernji list* and *Jutarnji list*.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia competed in the Eurovision Song Contest as part of Yugoslavia since 1961.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The first and only victory Yugoslavia achieved in the competition was accomplished by the Croatian pop band Riva in 1989.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Since its debut at the 1993 contest, Croatia won two fourth places at the 1996 and 1999 contests, and one second place at the 2024 contest, marking the country's best result to date as an independent nation.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia's film industry is small and heavily subsidised by the government, mainly through grants approved by the Ministry of Culture with films often being co-produced by HRT.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatian cinema produces between five and ten feature films per year.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Pula Film Festival, the national film awards event held annually in Pula, is the most prestigious film event featuring national and international productions.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Animafest Zagreb, founded in 1972, is the prestigious annual film festival dedicated to the animated film.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The first greatest accomplishment by Croatian filmmakers was achieved by Dušan Vukotić when he won the 1961 Academy Award for Best Animated Short Film for *Ersatz* (Croatian: *Surogat*).
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatian film producer Branko Lustig won the Academy Awards for Best Picture for *Schindler's List* and *Gladiator*.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Here We Go Again* on island of Vis, *Succession* on the island of Korčula, *Hercules*, *The Weekend Away*, *Bliss* in Split, *The Peacemaker*, *Lee* and many others.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia became international filming location due to its biodiversity, landscape that can accommodate every visual requirements and cheaper filming costs.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In last 11 years there has been 122 projects for international films in Croatia, and €263 million spent as part of the Filming in Croatia which increased in last years due to high demand for its location.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatian traditional cuisine varies from one region to another.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Dalmatia and Istria have culinary influences of Italian and other Mediterranean cuisines which prominently feature various seafood, cooked vegetables and pasta, and condiments such as olive oil and garlic.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Austrian, Hungarian, Turkish, and Balkan culinary styles influenced continental cuisine.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In that area, meats, freshwater fish, and vegetable dishes are predominant.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] There are two distinct wine-producing regions in Croatia.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The continental in the northeast of the country, especially Slavonia, produces premium wines, particularly whites.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Along the north coast, Istrian and Krk wines are similar to those in neighbouring Italy, while further south in Dalmatia, Mediterranean-style red wines are the norm.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Annual production of wine exceeds 72 million litres as of 2017.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia was almost exclusively a wine-consuming country up until the late 18th century when a more massive beer production and consumption started.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] There are 11 restaurants in Croatia with a Michelin star and 89 restaurants bearing some of the Michelin's marks.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatia has a long tradition of sports dating back to Roman times, followed by popular medieval knights' tournaments.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Modern organized sports began in the late 19th century with the founding of sports associations like Hrvatski Sokol in 1874.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] By the early 20th century, many sports organizations emerged, including the Croatian Sports Association established in 1909.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatian sports' development has been closely related to the Olympic movement, with Franjo Bučar playing a key role in promoting sports for Croatian independence.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Sport is part of the school curriculum, and many children engage in extracurricular activities.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] To support sports development, Croatia enacted the National Sport Programme in 2019.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Funding for sports comes from the state budget, sponsorship, and membership fees.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The Croatian Olympic Committee, established in 1991, oversees over 80 national sports associations.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The most popular sports in Croatia are football, basketball, handball, and water polo.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In 2024, there were over 4,500 chess association members.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] With about 12,500 sports associations, football is the most popular sport, hosting nearly 1,500 clubs and 110,000 players, achieving significant milestones, including bronze at the 1998 World Cup, silver at the 2018 World Cup and another bronze at 2022 World Cup.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Croatians have participated in the Olympics since 1992 and have won 59 Olympic medals, including 20 gold.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The national tennis team has won two Davis Cup titles and won a gold medal at the 2020 Summer Olympics in men's doubles.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] The national handball and water polo teams are also been successful, each achieving multiple championships and medals.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] Rowing has seen success as well, winning multiple Olympic and World Championship medals.
[src:croatia/croatia-p02] In gymnastics, athletes have also made their mark, winning medals in European and World Championships.
[src:croatia/eu] The .eu ccTLD was approved by ICANN on 22 March 2005 and put in the Internet root zone on 2 May 2005.
[src:croatia/eu] Even though the EU is not a country (it is a sui generis intergovernmental and supranational organisation), it has an exceptional reservation in ISO 3166.
[src:croatia/eu] The Commission and ICANN had extended negotiations lasting more than five years to secure its acceptance.
[src:croatia/eu] The sunrise period was broken into two phases.
[src:croatia/eu] The first phase, which began on 7 December 2005 was to facilitate applications by registrants with prior rights based on trademarks and geographic names.
[src:croatia/eu] The second phase began on 7 February 2006 and covered company, trade and personal names.
[src:croatia/eu] In the case of all Sunrise applications, the application needed to be accompanied by documents proving the claim to ownership of a certain right.
[src:croatia/eu] The decision was then made by PricewaterhouseCoopers Belgium, which had been chosen as the validation agent by EURid.
[src:croatia/eu] On 7 February 2006, the registry was opened for company, trade and personal names.
[src:croatia/eu] In the first 15 minutes, there were 27,949 total applications, and after one hour, 71,235.
[src:croatia/eu] On 7 April 2006 at 11 am CET registration became possible for non-trademark holders.
[src:croatia/eu] Most people requesting domains had asked their registrars to put their requested domains in a queue, ensuring the best chance to register a domain.
[src:croatia/eu] This way more than 700,000 domains were registered during the first 4 hours of operation.
[src:croatia/eu] Some large registrars like GoDaddy and small registrars like Dotster suffered from long queues and unresponsiveness, allowing people to 'beat the queue' by registering through a registrar that had already processed its queue.
[src:croatia/eu] By August 2006, 2 Million .eu domains had been registered.
[src:croatia/eu] It was then fourth-largest ccTLD in Europe, after .de, .uk and .nl, and is one of the largest internationally.
[src:croatia/eu] The number of .eu domain registrations during the year after the landrush 7 April 2006 to 6 April 2007 seems to have peaked at approximately 2.6 million .eu domains.
[src:croatia/eu] The market adjustment that follows a landrush in any domain name extension ensures that the number of registered domains will fall as many speculative domain registrations that failed to be resold will not be renewed.
[src:croatia/eu] This is sometimes referred to as the *Junk Dump*.
[src:croatia/eu] On the morning of 7 April 2007, the number of active .eu domains stood at 2,590,160 with approximately 15,000 domains having been deleted since 5 April 2007.
[src:croatia/eu] Approximately 1.5 million .eu domains were up for renewal in April 2007.
[src:croatia/eu] The EURid registry software is based on the DNS.be software and domains are physically renewed at the end of the month of their anniversary of registration.
[src:croatia/eu] This process differs from more sophisticated registries like that of .com TLD and other ccTLDs that operate on a daily basis.
[src:croatia/eu] As with any post-landrush phase, an extension shrinks as the *Junk Dump* takes effect.
[src:croatia/eu] Over one year after the launch of .eu (5 July 2007), the number of .de domains registered was 11,079,557 according to the German .de registry's statistics page, while number of German owned .eu domains according to EURid's statistics page was 796,561.
[src:croatia/eu] The number of .uk domains registered was 6,038,732 according to .uk registry Nominet's statistics page.
[src:croatia/eu] The number of apparently UK owned .eu domains was 344,584.
[src:croatia/eu] The extent of the shrinkage of .eu ccTLD is difficult to estimate because EURid does not publish detailed statistics on the number of new domains registered each day.
[src:croatia/eu] Instead it provides only a single figure for the number of active domains.
[src:croatia/eu] The number of new registrations are combined with numbers of domains registered.
[src:croatia/eu] Approximately 250,000 .eu domains were either deleted or moved into quarantine by 30 April 2007.
[src:croatia/eu] In the intervening years the renewal rate has stabilised to approximately 80%, which is above the industry average.
[src:croatia/eu] As of November 2019, according to the Tranco rank, the top 100 thousand most popular domains in the world included over 200 .eu domains.
[src:croatia/eu] The commission announced on 27 April 2018 that it would like to open registration to all EU and EEA citizens, including those living outside the EU.
[src:croatia/eu] The Parliament, the council, and the Commission reached an agreement on this in December 2018, and the corresponding regulation passed the Parliament on 31 January 2019.
[src:croatia/eu] The 317,000 British .eu domain names were subject to Brexit negotiations because the .eu domain is reserved for European Union use.
[src:croatia/eu] The .eu Brexit would have occurred on 30 March 2020, in case of no deal, but had since been postponed to January 2021.
[src:croatia/eu] The UK-EU free trade deal does not cover .eu domains.
[src:croatia/eu] The United Kingdom Government released guidance for British citizens regarding .eu domains in October 2020, and .eu holders with a British address attached have been contacted twice by the domain registry regarding their domains – once in October 2020, once in December 2020.
[src:croatia/eu] British citizens had their .eu domains suspended on 1 January 2021 for six months, and then withdrawn on 1 July 2021 after a grace period to allow EU/EEA citizens to update the registration information to show their non-UK address.
[src:croatia/eu] From 1 January 2022, they were revoked and made available for registration by other entities.
[src:croatia/eu] This is the first case of its kind where an institution managing an internet top-level domain has withdrawn domains *en masse* for an entire country.
[src:croatia/eu] The second-level domain .europa.eu has been reserved for EU institution sites, with institutions and agencies making the switch from .eu.int to .europa.eu domains on the Europe day of 9 May 2006.
[src:croatia/eu] EURid has a rule that the second-level domain name must be in the same script as the top-level domain, so Cyrillic second-level domains must go under .ею instead of .eu, and all domain names under .ею must be spelt using Cyrillic.
[src:croatia/eu] Older Cyrillic domains under .eu were cloned into .ею at its launch.
[src:croatia/eu] As of March 2024, there are 1,486 registered domains under .ею.
[src:croatia/eu] An application for a top-level domain using Greek letters, **.ευ** was submitted in 2016.
[src:croatia/eu] The application was originally turned down because it was too visually similar to .eu.
[src:croatia/eu] The Greek name of the EU is Ευρωπαϊκή Ένωση (ΕΕ), but .εε would be too visually similar to .ee, the top-level domain of Estonia.
[src:croatia/eu] In 2019 steps were taken towards approving .ευ as a domain.
[src:croatia/eu] As of March 2024, there are 2,595 registered domains under .ευ.
[src:croatia/eu] Domain name speculation, domain name warehousing and cybersquatting are always features of the launch of any new TLD; however, this was more widespread in the case of the .eu launch.
[src:croatia/eu] Bob Parsons, CEO and co-founder of GoDaddy, criticized the landrush process designed by EURid.
[src:croatia/eu] Particularly, he condemned the use of shell companies by some registrars.
[src:croatia/eu] These "phantom" registrars effectively had hundreds of opportunities of registering a domain whereas a genuine registrar effectively only had one opportunity to register the same domain.
[src:croatia/eu] Thus some registrants were crowded out of the .eu landrush process and many generic .eu domain names are now owned by the companies using these "phantom" registrars.
[src:croatia/eu] Patrik Lindén, spokesman for EURid at the time, denied the allegations by Parsons, stating that "[EURid] verified that each registrar was an individual legal entity.
[src:croatia/eu] Each had to sign an agreement with us, and prepay €10,000." Parsons did not dispute that each registrar was a separate legal entity, but noted that creating such entities was trivial: "Mr.
[src:croatia/eu] Linden seemed proud that the EURid registry verified that each applicant was a legal entity before it was accredited.
[src:croatia/eu] Take a moment and think about what that means.
[src:croatia/eu] You can form a "legal entity" for $50 – an LLC – and you are good to go.
[src:croatia/eu] While speculative activity occurred with the launch of other domains, it was the scale of the activity that called into question the competence of EURid in protecting the integrity of eu ccTLD.
[src:croatia/eu] The EURid organisation investigated some allegations of abuse, and in July 2006 announced the suspension of over 74,000 domain names and that they were suing 400 registrars for breach of contract.
[src:croatia/eu] The status of the domains was changed from *active* to *on-hold*.
[src:croatia/eu] This meant that the domains could not be moved or have their ownership changed.
[src:croatia/eu] The registrars also lost their access to the EURid registration database meaning that they could no longer register .eu domain names.
[src:croatia/eu] The legal action relates to the practice of domain name warehousing, whereby large numbers of domain names are registered, often by registrars, with the intention of subsequently selling them on to third parties.
[src:croatia/eu] EURid rules state that applications for domains can only be made after a legitimate application has been made to a registrar.
[src:croatia/eu] The 74,000 applications were made in the name of only three Cyprus registered companies – Ovidio Ltd., Fausto Ltd. and Gabino Ltd.
[src:croatia/eu] The affected registrars, joined in the action by the affected registrants, obtained a provisional order from the Court of First Instance in Brussels, Belgium on 27 September 2006.
[src:croatia/eu] The court ordered EURid to release the blocked domain names or else pay a fine of €25,000 per hour for each affected domain name.
[src:croatia/eu] EURid complied with the court order and changed the status of the domains from *on-hold* to *active* and restored EURid registration database access to the affected registrars.
[src:croatia/hr] The .hr domain is administered by CARNET (Croatian Academic and Research Network), via the CARNET DNS Committee which determines policy, and the CARNET DNS Service which handles day-to-day matters.
[src:croatia/hr] The committee is composed of members generally associated with the academic community.
[src:croatia/hr] Until 2010, the Service was operated by SRCE; since 1 July 2010 the service operations are divided between CARNET itself, SRCE and a variety of registrars.
[src:croatia/hr] Registrants are classified into a number of different groups with different rules about their domain registrations.
[src:croatia/hr] A requirement of connection to Croatia, such as being a citizen, permanent resident, registered company or EU company with VAT ID evidenced in the VIES system, is common to all of the categories except for the .com.hr.
[src:croatia/hr] Third level domains (example.com.hr) are allowed to be registered for anyone in the world as long as they provide a local contact.
[src:croatia/hr] There are also third-level registrations including of individuals in a few specialized domains such as **.iz.hr** (**.from.hr**), and an unlimited number of registrations in **.com.hr**, but these are unpopular compared to the second-level names registered directly under **.hr**.
[src:croatia/hr] As of March 2017, around 30.33% of all the .hr domains were served via secured HTTPS protocol, with the cPanel, Inc.
[src:croatia/hr] Certification Authority being the most popular SSL certificate.
[src:croatia/hr] Apache is the most popular web server, serving 65.93% of the .hr domains, followed by Microsoft-IIS serving 13.23% of the total .hr domains.
[src:croatia/hr] As of 14 December 2017 at 3PM CET, over 100,000 .hr domain names are registered.
